04349nam a22006975i 9780228006893DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280068937 a10.1515/97802280068932doi  a(DE-B1597)656806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD6250.F82b.G677 2021 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a331.3109442231 aGossard, Julia M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYoung Subjects :bChildren, State-Building, and Social Reform in the Eighteenth-Century French World /cJulia M. Gossard. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b5 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStates, People, and the History of Social Change00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tInvesting in Children: Lyon’s Charitable Community -- tThe Lyonnais Laboratory: Educational Experimentation -- tChildren Spread Reform -- tParisian Children of the State -- tTrafficking in Children: Pronatalism and Population in North America -- tChildren of the Empire: Cruxes of Imperial Strategy -- tEpilogue: A Revolution in Childhood -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the metropole, the colonies, and the wider eighteenth-century world, French children and youth participated in a diverse set of state-building initiatives, social reform programs, and imperial expansion efforts. Young Subjects explores the lives and experiences of these youth, revealing their role as active and vital agents in the shaping of early modern France.Through a set of regional case studies, Julia Gossard demonstrates how thousands of children and youth were engaged in the service of the state. In Lyon, charity schools cultivated children as agents of moral and social reform who carried their lessons home to their families. In Paris, orphaned and imprisoned youth trained in skilled trades or prepared for military service, while others were sent to the French colonies in North America as filles du roi and sturdy labourers. Young people from merchant families were recruited to serve as cultural brokers and translators on behalf of French commerical interests in the Ottoman Empire and Siam. In each case, Gossard considers how these youth played, negotiated, and sometimes resisted their roles, and what expressions of individual identity and agency were available to subjects under the legal control of others.As sources of labour, future taxpayers, colonial subjects, cultural mediators, and potential criminals, children and youth were objects of intense interest for civic authorities. Young Subjects refocuses our attention on these often overlooked historical subjects who helped to build France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChild laborzFrancexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aFrance.  aFrench.  aagency.  ababies.  ababy.  achildhood.  achildren.  aearly modern.  aeighteenth century.  aexperiences.  agender.  ainfants.  akids.  apremodern.  asocial reform.  astate building.  asubjecthood.  ateens.  ayouth.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228006893?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228006893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228006893/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles